<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>Analyzing the relationship between authors, articles, and their citation network, the environment can automatically discover knowledge flow networks and can distinguish the type of knowledge nodes using ranking algorithms and trace their evolution.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>This service can discover global interest groups by finding two types of citation relationship.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>if there is a citation path in each direction between two articles, then the authors share common interest and knowledge.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>(4) Automatically discover interest groups.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>Searching the citation network among Web pages and in digital libraries can reveal knowledge flows among authors.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>The system can display users' personal knowledge flow networks by finding their citations and their co-authors' citations, classifying the articles involved by discipline and chronology, expressing the category semantics for advanced services, linking the categories with the citations, and revealing knowledge flows using the citation network.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>analyzing the relationships between results to enrich a knowledge flow network;</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>This service can help scientists select peers by finding the dense cliques in knowledge flow networks by looking at the statistical results and distribution of authors, articles, and citations.</a>
<a name="8">[8]</a> <a href="#8" id=8>(1) Outline personal research roadmaps and depict the evolution of interest and knowledge.</a>
<a name="9">[9]</a> <a href="#9" id=9>This service can recommend references by retrieving documents from the Web and digital libraries, ranking them according to their citation rates and the roles of the authors, and tracing and analyzing their citation networks to show the references as a network rather than as a list.</a>
